06313nam a22007455i 9780231540421DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2015009578  a(OCoLC)984546714  a97802315404217 a10.7312/brow173422doi  a(DE-B1597)458262  a(OCoLC)914192165  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aHC79.E5bE25253 2015 4aHC79.E5 7aSCI0200002bisacsh04a333.700aEcological Economics for the Anthropocene :bAn Emerging Paradigm /ced. by Peter Timmerman, Peter Brown.  aPilot project. eBook available to selected US libraries only 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (408 p.) :b20 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. The Ethics of Re-Embedding Economics in the Real: Case Studies -- t2. Ethics for Economics in the Anthropocene -- t3. Justice Claims Underpinning Ecological Economics -- t4. Measurement of Essential Indicators in Ecological Economics -- t5. Boundaries and Indicators -- t6. Revisiting the Metaphor of Human Health for Assessing Ecological Systems and Its Application to Ecological Economics -- t7. Following in Aldo Leopold’s Footsteps -- t8. Toward an Ecological Macroeconomics -- t9. New Corporations for an Ecological Economy: A Case Study -- t10. Ecological Political Economy and Liberty -- t11. A New Ethos, a New Discourse, a New Economy -- tCONCLUSION. Continuing the Journey of Ecological Economics -- tContributors -- tIndex -- tFOREWORD -- tINTRODUCTION. The Unfinished Journey of Ecological Economics0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEcological Economics for the Anthropocene provides an urgently needed alternative to the long-dominant neoclassical economic paradigm of the free market, which has focused myopically—even fatally—on the boundless production and consumption of goods and services without heed to environmental consequences. The emerging paradigm for ecological economics championed in this new book recenters the field of economics on the fact of the Earth's limitations, requiring a total reconfiguration of the goals of the economy, how we understand the fundamentals of human prosperity, and, ultimately, how we assess humanity's place in the community of beings.Each essay in this volume contributes to an emerging, revolutionary agenda based on the tenets of ecological economics and advances new conceptions of justice, liberty, and the meaning of an ethical life in the era of the Anthropocene. Essays highlight the need to create alternative signals to balance one-dimensional market-price measurements in judging the relationships between the economy and the Earth's life-support systems. In a lively exchange, the authors question whether such ideas as "ecosystem health" and the environmental data that support them are robust enough to inform policy. Essays explain what a taking-it-slow or no-growth approach to economics looks like and explore how to generate the cultural and political will to implement this agenda. This collection represents one of the most sophisticated and realistic strategies for neutralizing the threat of our current economic order, envisioning an Earth-embedded society committed to the commonwealth of life and the security and true prosperity of human society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aEcologyxEconomic aspects. 0aEnvironmental economics. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Ecology.2bisacsh1 aBrown, Peter G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Peter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDuguay, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/